name: Nina Pineda

content: Last night we did a story about a NJ couple scammed by someone online posing as member of the military. We wondered... how did the scammer get what looked to be a valid military ID? Well, late yesterday we finally tracked down the man in the (fuzzed out) Air Force ID... who told us he was in the military, but was selling his car online. A buyer contacted him - the two got to talking. The buyer (who was actually a scammer) wanted proof that the man was in the military before he would send out money to him. So this man unwittingly emailed a picture of his military ID to someone he thought would buy his car. He didn't know he was emailing a scammer. Mind you, this man, who's currently in the Air Force - didn't lose money in the deal - but he's now discovering that his ID is being used to con others.... So be on the look out!!! Trust... but verify!
